{You naturally respond 2\D to North's strong 2\C opener. Before you know it you are playing a slam - with your mighty 2-point hand! South plays 6\D. West leads the \SQ.

If the contract appears to depend upon a finesse, try to find another way. Here, you can always try the \C finesse, but maybe you can eliminate \Ss and see what happens.

Win the \SA, play the \D4 to the \D10, and ruff a \S with the \DQ. Both opponents followed to the trump. 

Play the \D7 to the \DJ and ruff the last \S with the \DK.

Having eliminated the \Ds and \Ss, now remove the \Hs. Play \HA, \HK, and ruff a \H. 

At last it is time to play \Cs. Lead a \C from your hand and play dummy's \C9 if West plays low. East will win the trick but will be end-played, forced to either play a \C back to dummy's \C A Q, or give you a ruff-sluff. 

If West puts on either the \CT or \CJ you play dummy's \CQ. If East can win with the \CK he will once again be end-played, forced to either play a \C back to dummy's \CA 9, or give you a ruff-sluff.

The A Q 9 combination is interesting. Obviously if you have A Q 10 it works very well in an end-play situation. 

As you see, A Q 9 actually works just as well.}
[Play "W"]SQ

